'''Vim''' ('''V'''i '''im'''proved) is a text editor based on [[Wikipedia:Vi|vi]]. It can be used from the command line or as a standalone application with graphical user interface.

== Instalación ==

=== Instalación de la aplicación ===

To install Vim with both the ncurses-based interface ({{Path|/usr/bin/vim}})) and the graphical interface (for the X Window System - {{Path|/usr/bin/gvim}}), install {{Package|app-editors/gvim}}:

{{Emerge|app-editors/gvim}}

También hay una interfaz experimenta [[Qt]] llamada {{Package|app-editors/vim-qt}}.

Si no se necesita soporte del sistema X Window, simplemente se puede instalar {{Package|app-editors/vim}}:

{{Emerge|app-editors/vim}}

=== Extensiones ===

La categoría ''app-vim'' ofrece una gran cantidad de definiciones adicionales de sintaxis, plugins y otros elementos relacionados con Vim.

Use <tt>emerge</tt> or <tt>eix</tt> to get an overview of available packages in the ''app-vim'' category:

{{Cmd|emerge --search "%@^app-vim"
|eix -cC app-vim}}

== Usar Vim ==

=== Comenzar ===

Vim has a built-in tutorial which should require around 30 min to go through. Start it using the <tt>vimtutor</tt> command:

{{Cmd|vimtutor}}

== Consejos y trucos ==

=== Usar Vim como ex o ed desde la línea de órdenes ===

It is possible to use Vim for one-liners — commands that can be used in scripts or on the command line to make changes in an unattended manner.

For instance, the following command adds <code>#</code> to the beginning of each line in the {{Path|file.txt}} file:

{{Cmd|vim -c ":%s/^/#/g" -c ":x" fichero.txt}}

What happens is that Vim interprets the passed on commands (through the <code>-c</code> option). The first command is Vim's substitution command (which is very similar to <tt>sed</tt>'s), the second one is Vim's instruction to save and exit the editor.

=== Change file encoding ===

To change the file encoding of a file to [[UTF-8]], use the following command (in Vim command mode):

{{Cmd|e ++enc{{=}}utf8|prompt=:|color=orange}}

As shown in the previous trick, it is possible to do this from the command line as well:

{{Cmd|vim -c ":wq! ++enc{{=}}utf8" fichero.txt}}

